fields.name: Get a hint
fields.text:
Agent,

While conducting forensic analysis of the disk on an editor's computer,
we found some classic indicators of compromise and found an exploit used in the wild.

It's a common exploit, but it's been heavily obfuscated and modified to avoid AV detection.
This modification doesn't seem be done by hand and we're puzzled as to how they did it.

We've also found this strange file with an odd extension which is attached for you below.
We're not sure what this is, and the editor certainly doesn't remember downloading such file.

If they're using a common exploit, then maybe that file might already be in an open source domain somewhere?

We also think the group have access to a large amount of GPU computing power. Although, we can't
ship you a new GPU, we would advise that you checkout https://bit.ly/3hodu4S for help with regards
to that.

Also to analyse the video, we recommend you use something stable like VLC and Windows 10. Totem on Ubuntu
is specifically known to have issues with playback of certain formats.

Good luck!

You might also find this useful - https://files-elite.ractf.co.uk/13/reveal.h5

fields.name: Get a hint

Agent,

It might be worth trawling though some public source code repositories, to see if anything exists which can find secrets hidden within this type of audio file format.

When dealing with source code you may need to compile code, but I'm confident you'll be able to do that as required.

Good luck, I look forward to what you uncover.

fields.name: Not so Algorithmic
fields.description:
I decided to encrypt some data using the script at [url], but I managed to loose the data and all I have now is the encrypted version. Can you try and recover the original data for me?

Cipher 1: `7r7wHPNxCE4SfkzAwkQCXIglGusIAlgeQIHgQU6eEGjegn2wXGoqRQSYB/GWzMyw`

Cipher 2: `rt0Hdb8KfZHHRP0GcIMl5h8xcCbLtJJO4bbQ0XeQnhJGOGZab397cCXQ7q0Vfbd3`

```python
from Crypto.Util.Padding import pad
from Crypto.Cipher import AES
from gmpy2 import mpz, invert, t_mod, sub, add, mul, bit_test, num_digits
import base64
import os


# Number of high bits to discard
BITS_TO_CHOP = 12
# A convenience bitmask to discard bits
CHOP_MASK = 2 ** (256 - BITS_TO_CHOP) - 1


class P256:
    # https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/Legacy/SP/nistspecialpublication800-90r.pdf
    p = 0xffffffff00000001000000000000000000000000ffffffffffffffffffffffff
    a = -3
    b = 0x5ac635d8aa3a93e7b3ebbd55769886bc651d06b0cc53b0f63bce3c3e27d2604b
    q = 0xffffffff00000000ffffffffffffffffbce6faada7179e84f3b9cac2fc632551
    gx = 0x6b17d1f2e12c4247f8bce6e563a440f277037d812deb33a0f4a13945d898c296
    gy = 0x4fe342e2fe1a7f9b8ee7eb4a7c0f9e162bce33576b315ececbb6406837bf51f5

    @classmethod
    def G(cls):
        return Point(cls.gx, cls.gy)


class Point:
    """
    A point on P256. This makes heavy use of gmpy2 to ensure the code executes
    in a reasonable amount of time. Operator overloading was used to make the
    experience of using this class a little nicer.
    """
    INF = None

    def __init__(self, x, y):
        self.xy = x, y

    def __eq__(self, other):
        return self.x == other.x and self.y == other.y

    def __add__(self, other):
        if self == self.INF:
            return other
        elif other == self.INF:
            return self
        elif self == -other:
            return self.INF
        else:
            dy = sub(other.y, self.y)
            dx = invert(sub(other.x, self.x), P256.p)
            lambda_ = t_mod(mul(dy, dx), P256.p)

            x = t_mod(sub(sub(mul(lambda_, lambda_), self.x), other.x), P256.p)
            y = t_mod(sub(mul(lambda_, sub(self.x, x)), self.y), P256.p)

            return Point(x, y)

    @property
    def xy(self):
        return self.x, self.y
    @xy.setter
    def xy(self, xy):
        self.x, self.y = xy

    def double(self):
        num = add(mul(mul(self.x, self.x), 3), P256.a)
        denom = invert(mul(self.y, 2), P256.p)
        lambda_ = t_mod(mul(num, denom), P256.p)

        x = t_mod(sub(sub(mul(lambda_, lambda_), self.x), self.x), P256.p)
        y = t_mod(sub(mul(lambda_, sub(self.x, x)), self.y), P256.p)

        return Point(x, y)

    def __radd__(self, other):
        return self + other

    def __mul__(self, scalar):
        if scalar == 0:
            return self.INF

        R0 = Point(*self.xy)
        R1 = self.double()

        dbits = num_digits(scalar, 2)

        i = dbits - 2
        while i >= 0:
            if bit_test(scalar, i):
                R0 += R1
                R1 = R1.double()
            else:
                R1 += R0
                R0 = R0.double()
            i -= 1

        return R0

    def __rmul__(self, scalar):
        return self * scalar

    def __neg__(self):
        if self == self.INF:
            return self

        return Point(self.x, -self.y % P256.p)
# Define a point at infinity.
Point.INF = Point(0, 1)


class DualEC:
    def __init__(self, seed, P, Q):
        self.seed = seed
        self.P, self.Q = P, Q

    def genbits(self):
        """
        Cycle the PRNG and grab the next value.
        """
        t = self.seed
        s = (t * self.P).x
        self.seed = s
        r = (s * self.Q).x
        # Up to this point, `r` is an mpz(), so we convert it back to an int.
        return int(r) & CHOP_MASK  # Discard high bits

    def get256(self):
        # `genbits` doesn't return a full 256 bits as a security measure.
        # This is an issue for generating 256-bit integers, so we fill the dead
        # space with some bytes from a second PRNG call.
        high = self.genbits()
        low = self.genbits()
        return (high << (BITS_TO_CHOP)) | (low >> (256 - BITS_TO_CHOP * 2))


def main():
    # See: Appendix A.1 of NIST SP 800-90
    P = Point(
        48439561293906451759052585252797914202762949526041747995844080717082404635286,
        36134250956749795798585127919587881956611106672985015071877198253568414405109
    )
    # SP 800-90 probably has a backdoor, so I picked my own value for Q!
    # Q = P * ((0x942234e7dcb9ba1d4b31ed55881953fed2aa702ce1fc43572f0475e0f600bab7 ** (P256.q - 2)) % P256.q)
    Q = Point(
        100508144069647648269243464262168198266074415623308668240805976507537794634889,
        21204921157069367629735872129113479234458862923292364275439134374707064710554
    )

    seed = int.from_bytes(os.urandom(8), 'big')
    ec = DualEC(seed, P, Q)

    # Generate two 16 bit integers
    ivs = ec.get256()
    iv1, iv2 = ivs >> 128, ivs & ((1 << 128) - 1)

    # Use the PRNG to pick two keys for AES
    key1 = ec.get256()
    key2 = ec.get256()

    # PyCryptodome needs bytes, not ints, so convert everything as needed
    key1, key2 = int.to_bytes(key1, 32, 'big'), int.to_bytes(key2, 32, 'big')
    iv1, iv2 = int.to_bytes(iv1, 16, 'big'), int.to_bytes(iv2, 16, 'big')

    # Setup the pair of AES-256-CBC instances. Block size = 16 bytes.
    cipher1 = AES.new(key1, AES.MODE_CBC, iv1)
    cipher2 = AES.new(key2, AES.MODE_CBC, iv2)

    FLAG = open('flag.txt', 'rb').read()

    # Encrypt the flag half-and-half
    ct1 = cipher1.encrypt(pad(FLAG[:len(FLAG) // 2], 16))
    ct2 = cipher2.encrypt(pad(FLAG[len(FLAG) // 2:], 16))

    print('Cipher 1: ' + base64.b64encode(iv1 + ct1).decode())
    print('Cipher 2: ' + base64.b64encode(iv2 + ct2).decode())

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
```

fields.name: Good Luck
fields.description:
Agent,

We appreciate the strange times we're living through now.

Office may be closed, but our very tradecraft is not, our goal remains the same - to make the world a safer place.

We've seen a recent spike in cyber criminals sending highly compelling phishing emails with malicious attachments or links to high quality replicas of websites with seemingly similar domain names.

So, we've created a quirky summer challenge for you to solve. This should help brush up your skills and keep you alert.

We'd like to remind you that the devil truly does lie in the details.

Good luck!

```
Own a musket for home defense, since that's what the founding fathers intended. Four ruffians break into my house. "What the devil?" As I grab my powdered wig and Kentucky rifle. Blow a golf ball sized hole through the first man, he's dead on the spot. Draw my pistol on the second man, miss him entirely because it's smoothbore and nails the neighbors dog. I have to resort to the cannon mounted at the top of the stairs loaded with grape shot, "Tally ho lads" the grape shot shreds two men in the blast, the sound and extra shrapnel set off car alarms. Fix bayonet and charge the last terrified rapscallion. He Bleeds out waiting on the police to arrive since triangular bayonet wounds are impossible to stitch up. Just as the founding fathers intended.
```
fields.author: Linus

fields.name: Boppin' Tunes
fields.description:
Agent,

Do you remember the intellectual property theft case we were working on a few months ago?

The investigation was relatively conclusive and we manged to foil their technique, but with regards to attribution, we never found out who was behind it.

However, we've seen a resurgence of the group. Another music studio has caught our attention after being compromised and having their unreleased tracks leaked in a similar fashion.

We're investigating the incident, it appears that they've switched up their techniques this time around.

We found a low resolution, out of sync, suspicious-looking music video of an already released track which we think contains some hidden information or secret.

We've attached the suspect file, can you take a look and see what you uncover?

TIP: We just need the name of this hidden information in lower case, with spaces swapped for underscores.

**RACTF Note: This is it, this is the Linus one, abandon hope all ye' who enter here.**

Agent,

It's PCAP forensics time! Umbrella corporation, a large biotech conglomerate, has asked us for assistance after their network technicians uncovered strange communications going from a host to a sketchy domain in their IDS sensor logs.

We examined the packets and didn't find anything contained within them. Needless to say this pattern of traffic seems strange and could indicate this host has been compromised. Umbrella has significant competition and hacktivists who are after them, so any loss of intellectual property could cost them a large amount financially.

We've replayed the traffic and captured it for you, can you examine it and see what's happening?

fields.name: Extreme Weebery
fields.description:
Time to put your OSINT skills to the test - can you get the final anime? 

In this challenge, you'll be given a series of clues. The first anime you have to find is the one from the screenshot given below, and the second clue refers to the first anime, giving you a second anime which you use in the 3rd clue, and so on. The final clue refers to one last anime, and the flag is that anime's full name written on MyAnimeList, wrapped in `elite{}`. 

For example, if you had the screenshot, and found an anime called A from it, if clue 2 was `The anime made by the same studio in the Year 2009`, you'd need to find the anime made by the studio that made anime A - let's call this new anime B. Then the 3rd clue would refer to another anime, this time involved with B, and this cycle continues until you find the very last anime!

Good luck! Your clues are as follows. 

1. Check out the screenshot, and find the anime which it is from!

2. Find the first season of the 2nd main arc of the most recent trading card anime voiced by the male lead from the show you just found.

3. Find the Japanese voice actor who voiced the main antagonist of the 1st season of the first arc of the above show.

4. Find the Japanese voice actor who voiced a character from a sports series that the voice actor found in Clue 3 also voiced in, in which the character is nicknamed a "Sea Otter".

5. Find the first movie in a famously long anime movie series where the voice actor from Clue 4 played the male lead for every movie.

6. Find the series recommended by 7 users on MyAnimeList in relation to the movie from Clue 5. This is your flag!

**NOTE: This challenge is literal hell in many ways, do not be afraid to DM me for hints if you get stuck.**
